# Next.js Component Conventions

## Core rule — Server Components are the default

**Every component must be a Server Component unless it has a specific reason not to be.**

The only valid reasons to add `"use client"` are:
- The component uses a React hook (`useState`, `useEffect`, `useActionState`, etc.)
- The component accesses browser-only APIs (`window`, `document`, etc.)
- The component uses a third-party library that requires a client boundary

`"use client"` must be placed on the **smallest possible leaf component** — the one that actually needs it. Never add it to a page, layout, or any wrapper that could remain a Server Component.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — entire page becomes a client bundle just for one interactive button
"use client";
export default function SettingsPage() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Settings</h1>       {/* static — didn't need to be client */}
      <UserInfo />             {/* static — didn't need to be client */}
      <DeleteAccountButton />  {/* only this needed "use client" */}
    </div>
  );
}

// ✅ GOOD — only the interactive leaf is a client component
export default function SettingsPage() {   // Server Component
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Settings</h1>
      <UserInfo />
      <DeleteAccountButton />  {/* "use client" lives inside this file only */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Page conventions
- Pages are `async` Server Components
- Read `searchParams` as a Promise (Next.js 15): `searchParams: Promise<{ key?: string }>`
- Export `metadata` from every page
- Pass URL data as plain props to children — never use `useSearchParams` in a Client Component when the page can read it first

## Route-scoped components
- Components used by only one route live in a `_components/` folder alongside the page
- The `_` prefix prevents Next.js treating the folder as a route segment

## Forms
- Form components should be Server Components using `action={serverAction}`
- Use `<SubmitButton>` from `@/components/submit-button` for pending state — it uses `useFormStatus` internally and works inside Server Component forms
- If `useActionState` is genuinely needed, extract only the stateful part into a client component; keep the surrounding form/layout as a Server Component

## Error state from actions
Redirect with `?error=` on failure so forms stay as Server Components.
Never return error strings from actions and catch them with `useActionState`.
